@article{Wang2013a,
	abstract = {We test the relativistic precession model (RPM) and the magnetohydrodynamics Alfv{\'e}n wave oscillation model (AWOM) for the kilohertz (kHz) quasi-periodic oscillations (QPOs) from sources with measured neutron star (NS) masses and twin kHz QPO frequencies. For the RPM, the derived NS masses of Cyg X-2, SAX J1808.4-3658 and 4U 1820-30 are 1.96 $\pm$ 0.10, 2.83 $\pm$ 0.04 and 1.85 $\pm$ 0.02 M&sun;, respectively. These are, respectively, ˜30, 100 and 40 per cent higher than the measured results 1.5 $\pm$ 0.3, <1.4 and 1.29^{+0.19}_{-0.07} M&sun;. For the AWOM, where the free parameter of the model is the density of the star, we infer the NS radii to be around 10-20 km for the above three sources. Based on this, we can infer the matter compositions inside the NSs with the help of the equations of state. In particular, for SAX J1808.4-3658, the AWOM shows a lower mass density for its NS than those of the other known kHz QPO sources, with a radius range of 17-20 km, which excludes the strange quark matter inside its star.},
